<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05001l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05001l">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05001l"> 1(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Agnes &amp; Thecla were with me</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Of that other life with God &hellip; little is known, save that he <font color="green">[St. Martin]</font> held continual and familiar intercourse with the inhabitants of heaven. This we learn from the following narrative in the <cite>Dialogues</cite> of Sulpicius Severus, in which the disciple Gallus is introduced as spokesman: &ldquo;One day as I and Sulpicius were keeping watch at his (Martin&apos;s) door &hellip; we heard the murmur of voices &hellip; After a lapse of two hours Martin joined us and &hellip; Sulpicius &hellip; implored him to explain the reason of that religious fear which we both acknowledged we had felt &hellip; &lsquo;I will tell you,&rsquo; he said; &lsquo;but I beseech you to reveal it to no one; <mark>Agnes, Thecla and Mary were with me</mark>,&rsquo; and he described the countenance and dress of each. <small> William Bullen Morris, <a name="WBML" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WBML"><cite title="source">The Life of Saint Patrick Apostle of Ireland</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1890) 82-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: SS. Agnes (3rd or 4th century) and Thecla (1st century) were martyrs who were regarded as special patronesses of purity. They both rejected earthly lovers and were prosecuted for that reason. </mm> </dd></dl>
